---
import Layout from "../components/Layout.astro";
import { SITE } from "../config.ts";

const jsonLd = {
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "AboutPage",
  name: "Methodology",
  url: new URL("/methodology", SITE.url).href,
  publisher: { "@type": "Organization", name: SITE.name, url: SITE.url },
};
---

<Layout
  title="Calculator Methodology"
  description="How PennyGrove's calculators work: the exact formulas, assumptions, and the automated tests that verify every result."
  path="/methodology"
  jsonLd={jsonLd}
>
  <div class="mx-auto max-w-3xl px-4 py-12">
    <h1 class="text-3xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-slate-900">Methodology</h1>
    <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-slate-400">Last reviewed: June 2026</p>
    <div class="prose-money mt-6">
      <p>
        We believe a money calculator is only worth using if you can trust the
        math. So here's exactly how every PennyGrove calculator works — the
        formulas, the assumptions, and how we verify the results. Nothing is a
        black box.
      </p>

      <h2>Every calculation is unit-tested</h2>
      <p>
        Our calculators are built on a single, shared financial-math library of
        pure functions. That library is covered by an automated test suite that
        pins each formula to known, independently-verifiable results (for example,
        a $1,000 lump sum at 10% compounded annually for 10 years must equal
        $2,593.74). Tests run automatically on every change before it can go live,
        so a math regression can't reach you.
      </p>

      <h2>The formulas we use</h2>

      <h3>Compound interest &amp; investment growth</h3>
      <p>
        Future value is computed month by month. A nominal annual rate compounded
        <em>m</em> times per year is converted to an effective monthly growth
        factor, then applied to the balance each month alongside any contributions.
        The lump-sum case reduces to the standard
        <code>FV = P × (1 + r/n)^(n·t)</code>.
      </p>

      <h3>Mortgage &amp; loan payments</h3>
      <p>
        Monthly principal and interest use the standard amortizing-loan formula
        <code>M = P · i / (1 − (1 + i)^−N)</code>, where <em>i</em> is the monthly
        rate and <em>N</em> the number of payments. We then build a full
        amortization schedule and add property tax, insurance, PMI (estimated at
        ~0.5%/yr of the loan when the down payment is under 20%) and HOA to show
        the complete PITI payment.
      </p>

      <h3>Home affordability</h3>
      <p>
        We work backwards from the <strong>28/36 rule</strong> — housing ≤ 28% of
        gross monthly income, total debt ≤ 36% — to the maximum payment, then solve
        algebraically for the loan and price (since taxes, insurance and PMI all
        scale with the home value).
      </p>

      <h3>Debt payoff (snowball &amp; avalanche)</h3>
      <p>
        We simulate month by month: interest accrues on each balance, minimum
        payments are applied, and any leftover budget is directed to the target
        debt — smallest balance first (snowball) or highest APR first (avalanche) —
        rolling freed-up payments forward as each debt is cleared.
      </p>

      <h3>Retirement, FIRE &amp; Coast FIRE</h3>
      <p>
        The FIRE number is your desired annual income divided by a safe withdrawal
        rate (4% by default — the &ldquo;25× expenses&rdquo; guideline). Retirement
        projections grow current savings plus contributions at your expected
        return and adjust the income target for inflation. Coast FIRE discounts the
        FIRE number back to today using a <em>real</em> (inflation-adjusted) return,
        so it's expressed in today's dollars.
      </p>

      <h3>Savings goal &amp; budget</h3>
      <p>
        The savings-goal tool solves the annuity future-value formula for the
        required monthly contribution. The budget tool applies the 50/30/20
        framework (or your custom split) to take-home pay.
      </p>

      <h2>Assumptions &amp; limitations</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>Results are <strong>estimates</strong> based on the figures you enter and the assumptions on each page.</li>
        <li>Returns and rates are not guaranteed; historical averages (like a ~7% long-run stock return) are references, not promises.</li>
        <li>We don't model taxes on investment gains, variable-rate loans, or every local fee. Real outcomes vary.</li>
        <li>Calculators run entirely in your browser — your numbers are never sent to a server.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Sources &amp; standards</h2>
      <p>
        The formulas above are standard financial mathematics used by banks and
        planners. Conceptual guidance in our articles draws on widely-accepted
        frameworks (the 4% rule from the Trinity Study and William Bengen's
        research; the 50/30/20 rule; the 28/36 lending guideline). For
        authoritative figures that change year to year — such as IRS contribution
        limits — we direct readers to the primary source rather than quoting numbers
        that may go stale.
      </p>

      <h2>Not financial advice</h2>
      <p>
        PennyGrove is an educational tools-and-information site, not a licensed
        advisor. Nothing here is personalized financial, tax, or investment advice.
        Confirm important decisions with a qualified professional. Found an error?
        Email <a href={`mailto:${SITE.email}`}>{SITE.email}</a> — we take accuracy
        seriously and fix issues quickly.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>
</Layout>
